snippet.textDisplay:
This is one of my first times watching your program and I enjoyed it. My daughter is a subscriber and she often talks about you and your observations. You seem very intelligent.
I wish you didn't use the epithet "Beautiful Bastards," for your viewers. I'm not a bastard. I'm not particularly beautiful, either, but that inaccuracy is easier for me to overlook. Or are you only addressing your subscribers? Actually, I would find that even more insulting, since my daughter, who is decidedly not a bastard, is a subscriber.
I like the way you address what's going on in the world. You seem to have a fairness that I find lacking in many news sources.



I agree with the penalties given to those who seem to be actively spreading the disease. I realize that some of these people are simply being recklessly impulsive. It seems that the media these days tends to encourage outrageous behavior. For some of these individuals, the maximum penalty of the law may be too severe. Hopefully, they would end up out early for good behavior and on probation. But the severity of the penalty is needed for a deterrent, in my opinion.


Thank you for the explanation of the unemployment situation. And thank you for covering something - anything - other than coronavirus.


I enjoyed your program. I may watch again. Thank you.

So people desperately wanting to get paid want to force more people to lose their income without anything to fall back on like the stimulus or unemployment.  This is like saying don't pay the employees at the grocery store or for the groceries you are hauling out because you don't have a check. It makes no sense to say screw over others because it benefits them rather than working with people. I'm sure decent landlords are going to be reasonable as they can be. But I bet the companies being paid to manage those rentals still demand to be paid by the landlord for doing their job, so he's not off the hook either. It's like no one thinks about how it all works. They aren't major corporations making big bank in most cases.

snippet.textDisplay: My rent is due on April 3rd and we are currently sitting with $400 in our bank account with close to that amount due in upcoming bills and only $900 expected to come in between now and the 3rd. We are paying the highest rent in our complex for what we are receiving, by at least $300 per month more than other local complexes with even more amenities. Our building is 60 years old and it has 5 owners. I guarantee these owners, who also own 15+ other buildings with astronomical rent prices compared to their local buildings, barely have a mortgage anymore and have plenty of money to sustain the buildings,  with no damage to their bank accounts, for several months. On top of that, they aren’t paying anything out on the properties because maintenance will not even enter a unit unless there is a major emergency and vendors will not come and do anything right now. Our rent has gone up so much that 6 tenants have moved out in the last month and no one has gone in to turn the units at all. I’m hoping for 2 things. 1. We get a rent freeze at least for April and 2. Rent is lowered for the empty units to the point that it would be cheaper for me to move to a different unit, downstairs (because I am disabled and have had to live on the top floor, with no elevator, for 7 years and it’s getting very difficult to walk up and down the stairs multiple times per day).
